X-AxSys wrote:Mixed emotions... If it substantially helps manage the war on drugs then so be it, evidence however suggests that not to be the case... On the other hand the wholesale delivery of such large volumes of what should be private data on a whim show just how lax our privacy laws are. You can clearly see the whole data privacy is heavily weighted toward private companies having no rights to use any data for any reason while government has unrestricted authority and power to demand consume and use/misuse that data anytime anywhere and for any reason...Even if it removes a substantial amount of drugs and/or drug traffickers from the streets, that level of invasion to mass privacy is not warranted. It isn't warranted for any reason, otherwise our Constitution is a sham.Our privacy laws are not lax. The enforcement of our laws is lax. Nonexistent, really. Unless you're a corporation that has ties to the government, of course. Then the enforcement of your privacy is equivalent to national security.The problem is that people need to stop looking at "I'll give up some privacy to keep _______ off the streets" (insert drugs; child pornographers; terrorists; illegal immigrants; etc,) and start demanding that their government find ways to "declare war" on all these different ideas without touching, damaging, infringing, or breaking any of the Constitutional rights for the innocent masses.
jdale
Ars Tribunus Militum
Tribus: US
Registered: Jun 27, 2011Posts: 2728
Posted: Tue Sep 03, 2013 10:44 am
While technically correct, the Ars article omits an extremely important point from the NYT source:Quote: It is queried for phone numbers of interest mainly using what are called “administrative subpoenas,” those issued not by a grand jury or a judge but by a federal agency, in this case the D.E.A. That's right, this data is received by the DEA with absolutely no court oversight.There is an aspect of this that is important and reasonable. In my opinion, the three problems are:1) No court oversight.2) 26 years is too much data to retain. Far, far beyond what is appropriate and necessary even for law enforcement purposes.3) No legal limitations on what else AT&T can do with this data, who they can share it with, who they can sell it to, etc.Resolve those three and it's fine with me. #1 is a pretty straightforward fix. #2 and #3 in my opinion require passing some real privacy laws, not just limitations on how the government works.
